# ArLibs API Usage Guide

This guide explains how to use the ArLibs API in your Minecraft plugins.

## Adding ArLibs as a Dependency

First, add ArLibs as a dependency in your plugin.yml:

```yaml
depend: [ArLibs]
```

## Using the Color Utility

The ColorUtil class provides methods for handling Minecraft text colors:

```kotlin
import dev.arteam.arlibs.utils.ColorUtil

// Standard color codes
val coloredText = ColorUtil.colorize("&aHello &bWorld!")

// Hex colors
val hexColoredText = ColorUtil.colorize("&#FF5733This is a custom color!")

// Gradient colors
val gradientText = ColorUtil.colorize("<g:#FF0000:#00FF00>This text transitions from red to green</g>")

// Rainbow colors
val rainbowText = ColorUtil.colorize("<r>This text is rainbow colored!</r>")
```

## Using the Logger Utility

The Logger class provides enhanced logging capabilities:

```kotlin
import dev.arteam.arlibs.utils.Logger
import org.bukkit.plugin.java.JavaPlugin

class MyPlugin : JavaPlugin() {
    private lateinit var logger: Logger
    
    override fun onEnable() {
        // Create a logger instance for your plugin
        logger = Logger.getLogger(this)
        
        // Or with debug mode enabled
        logger = Logger.getLogger(this, true)
        
        // Log messages with different levels
        logger.info("&aPlugin enabled successfully!")
        logger.warn("&eThis is a warning message")
        logger.error("&cThis is an error message")
        
        // Debug messages (only shown if debug mode is enabled)
        logger.debug("This is a debug message")
        
        // Log exceptions
        try {
            // Some code that might throw an exception
        } catch (e: Exception) {
            logger.exception("An error occurred", e)
        }
    }
}
```

## Best Practices

1. Always use the Logger utility instead of Bukkit's built-in logger for consistent formatting and color support.
2. Use ColorUtil for all text that will be displayed to players to ensure consistent color handling.
3. Keep your plugin's debug mode disabled in production to avoid unnecessary console spam.

